{{slim-wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
Recorded in {{etyl|enm|en}} since circa 1225, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|consentir|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term/t|la|cōnsentīre}}, present active infinitive of {{term/t|la|cōnsentiō||to feel together}}, itself from {{term|com-||with}} + {{term/t|la|sentiō||to feel}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/kənˈsɛnt/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-consent.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ɛnt}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To express [[willingness]], to give [[permission]].
#: ''I've '''consented''' to have the procedure performed.
#* {{rfdate}} Shakespeare
#*: My poverty, but not my will, '''consents'''.
# {{context|transitive|medicine|lang=en}} To cause to sign a consent form.
#* {{quote-journal|title=A randomized clinical trial to compare the effectiveness of canine lacebacks with reference to … |- ►maneyjournals.org [HTML]| author=T Usmani| coauthors=KD O'Brien, HV Worthington, S Derwent, D …| journal=Journal of Orthodontics| year=2002| passage=When the patient was '''consented''' to enter the study and registered, a telephone call was made to research assistant}}
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[grant]]; to [[allow]]; to [[assent]] to.
#* {{rfdate}} Milton
#*: Interpreters {{...}} will not '''consent''' it to be a true story.
# To agree in opinion or sentiment; to be of the same mind; to accord; to concur.
#* {{rfdate}} Bible, Acts viii. 1
#*: And Saul was '''consenting''' unto his death.
#* {{rfdate}} Fuller
#*: Flourishing many years before Wyclif, and much '''consenting''' with him in jugdment.

